Bio LPG has arrived in the Czech Republic, it promises ecological operation
Liquefied petroleum gas, abbreviated LPG (Liquefied Petroleum Gas), is a very well-known alternative fuel in the Czech Republic.
It is particularly popular because of its fundamentally lower price compared to gasoline or diesel fuel, given the significantly lower consumption tax, but its benefit is also lower CO2 emissions per kilometer traveled.
Similar to gasoline and diesel, it also has its environmentally friendly variant - &quot;bio LPG&quot;.
But it is quite new - it first appeared on the European market last year and, according to the press release of the Czech LPG Association, it arrived in the Czech Republic a few days ago.
&quot;These days we received the first fifteen tons of bio LPG, which will be mixed with classic fossil LPG and distributed to our gas stations,&quot; the association quotes Jiří Karlík from the Primagas company.
However, Bio LPG cannot be taken as bioethanol or biodiesel.
According to the association, it is chemically identical to classic petroleum LPG, which many motorists now fill their cars with.
Therefore, it is also possible to mix both versions at will.
&quot;The only difference compared to classic LPG is the production method,&quot; says Ivan Indráček, chairman of the association, about bio LPG.
This is also one of the great advantages of bio LPG compared to other alternative fuels.
It is easy to transport and store, and also the distribution infrastructure is quite good, for example compared to hydrogen or electricity.
Currently, this gas is obtained as a by-product in the production of bioethanol from food waste and sugar cane.
In the future, it should also be produced in a targeted manner, e.g. from cellulosic biomass, i.e. from wood waste.
In contrast, conventional petroleum LPG is produced partly as a by-product during oil refining, partly through separation during natural gas extraction.
As a result, depending on the production technology and the source, running a car on bio LPG is 40-70% more environmentally friendly in terms of carbon footprint than running on petroleum LPG and up to 90% compared to diesel.
But it is not about CO2 emissions from the car&#39;s exhaust, but about the ecology of fuel production, i.e. the so-called &quot;well-to-tank&quot; part.
Petrochemical companies Eni, Total and Neste are currently among the largest producers of bio LPG.
According to the recent update of the National Clean Mobility Action Plan (NAP ČM), Unipetrol is also investigating the possibility of production at its Litvín refinery.
According to the association&#39;s estimates, about 170,000 vehicles run on LPG in the Czech Republic; the Ministry of the Environment states in the NAP of the Czech Republic a slightly higher figure, roughly 200,000.
According to statistics from the Ministry of Transport, almost 6,000 conversions of LPG-powered cars were carried out last year alone.
It is possible to fill up with LPG in the Czech Republic at approximately 950 stations of various operators.
