Indoor air is up to five times worse than outdoor air.
Air fresheners and deodorants are harmful to health
Health is threatened not only by poor air quality in outdoor areas, but also at home.
This was pointed out by Israeli human health expert Carol Abraham, as quoted by The Jerusalem Post.
According to Abraham, who was instrumental in creating Israel&#39;s Ministry of Environmental Protection, household pollutants need to be addressed now that many people are spending more time working from home.
Abrahamová mentioned research by the US Environmental Agency (EPA), according to which the quality of indoor air is up to five times worse than outdoor air.
The World Health Organization (WHO) estimates that 3.8 million people die prematurely each year due to poor air quality in their homes.
&quot;Due to the coronavirus epidemic, which has forced and continues to force many to work from home, people have to spend more hours at home than before, so it&#39;s time to focus on indoor air quality,&quot; said Abraham.
In Israel, according to her, almost no one deals with the quality of &quot;home air&quot;.
At the same time, things that a person normally comes into contact with can be dangerous - paints, air fresheners, disinfectants, deodorants or pesticides.
&quot;Even the clothes that we regularly wear to the dry cleaners release poisonous gas,&quot; said Abrahamová.
According to her, children, elderly household members and people with respiratory problems are most at risk.
Even otherwise healthy individuals can begin to suffer from problems such as headaches, fainting, irritation of the nasal passages, nosebleeds, vomiting or skin allergies.
Long-term exposure to unhealthy substances can damage internal organs and the central nervous system.
However, not all pollutants come from objects inside households, the source can also be the material from which the houses are built.
